      "name": "Foundation Forge",
      "tagline": "Build the Platform",
      "weeks": "Weeks 1–5",
      "focuses": [
        "Build movement quality in free-weight patterns and introduce rotational power on a clean slate.",
        "Establish posterior chain resilience and shoulder durability under daily padel load."
      ],
      "message": {
        "paragraphs": [
          "This cycle is the platform everything else gets built on. You already have the sport hours — what you don't yet have is the free-weight base and the rotational engine that separates good padel players from elite ones.",
          "For the next five weeks, focus on owning every rep — tempo is the coach here, not the load. By the end of Cycle 1 you should feel noticeably more stable in your split stance, snappier out of low balls, and more durable through a full day of court work. Trust the tempo. The weight comes later."
        ],
        "outcomes": [
          "Cleaner free-weight patterns on trap bar and split squat",
          "Noticeably stronger eccentric control in Nordics and lateral decel",
          "Higher rotational power output on med-ball throws",
          "Reduced shoulder fatigue through daily padel sessions",
          "Copenhagen plank held cleanly for 30 seconds per side",
          "A durable foundation ready for heavy strength loading in Cycle 2"
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "num": 2,
      "name": "Strength Engine",
      "weeks": "Weeks 6–10",
      "focuses": [
        "Intensify compound strength (trap bar, split squat, bench) into the 3–5 rep range with heavier loading.",
        "Deepen unilateral capacity and close any left/right asymmetries exposed in Cycle 1."
      ],
      "teaser": {
        "subtitle": "The platform starts producing real output.",
        "paragraphs": [
          "Cycle 2 is where the reps drop, the loads climb, and everything you rehearsed in Cycle 1 gets tested under pressure. This is the phase that builds the strength your opponents will feel on the court.",
          "Earn it in these first five weeks — everything that follows depends on the base you lay here."
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "num": 3,
      "name": "Power Conversion",
      "weeks": "Weeks 11–15",
      "focuses": [
        "Convert raw strength into on-court power through contrast training and advanced plyometrics.",
        "Peak rotational velocity and reactive ability for in-season padel demands."
      ]
    },
    {
      "num": 4,
      "name": "Court Carryover",
      "weeks": "Weeks 16–20",
      "focuses": [
        "Maintain strength and power on minimal volume while sport demand rises.",
        "Sharpen deceleration, multi-directional speed, and recovery between high-intensity bouts."
      ]
