  "notes": {
    "greeting": "For You, Mahdi",
    "cards": [
      {
        "icon": "🎾",
        "title": "Gym Sits Under Padel, Not Over It",
        "body": "You're training padel daily — the gym is a supplement, not the main event. Always book gym sessions so the highest-intensity lifts (trap bar, med-ball throws, box jumps) sit at least 4–6 hours away from your hardest court session, or the morning after an easier on-court day. If a match or tough practice surprised you the day before, drop RPE by one point across the board. You won't lose adaptation — you'll protect it."
      },
      {
        "icon": "⏱",
        "title": "Tempo Is the Coach This Cycle",
        "body": "The numbers next to each exercise (e.g. 3-1-1-0) are eccentric – pause – concentric – reset, in seconds. Coming from a machine-dominant background, your free-weight patterns will only clean up if you respect the tempo. A 5-second Nordic descent at RPE 8 builds more eccentric strength than a 2-second descent at RPE 9 — and it carries over directly to deceleration on court. Don't let the ego shorten the down phase."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🌀",
        "title": "The Med-Ball Throw Is Your Most Important Lift",
        "body": "The rotational throw on Day 3 has the highest direct carryover to your padel swing of any exercise in this program. Treat every rep like a first-serve — full intent, full hip, full follow-through. If the trailing heel doesn't pop up off the floor, you threw with your arm and the rep doesn't count. Four quality reps per side beats eight sloppy ones every time."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🛡️",
        "title": "Protect the Shoulder — It's Already Working Daily",
        "body": "Padel gives your shoulder plenty of overhead volume already, which is why Cycle 1 has zero barbell overhead pressing. The landmine press and the cuff circuit on Day 2 aren't filler — they're what keeps you playing pain-free through Cycles 2 and 3. Don't skip them, don't rush them, and don't load them heavy. Slow reps, small muscles, big payoff."
      },
      {
        "icon": "🦵",
        "title": "The Copenhagen Plank Is Non-Negotiable",
        "body": "Padel is a lateral-dominant sport, and adductor strains are one of the most common shutdowns in racket athletes. The Copenhagen on Day 1 is the single best insurance policy available. Start on the knee version if the full version is too hard — just earn the time under tension. By Week 5 aim to hold 30 seconds per side cleanly."
      },
      {
        "icon": "😴",
        "title": "Your Sleep Is a Weapon — Keep It That Way",
        "body": "Sleep at 8/10 and 7–8 hours is exactly what a daily-training pro needs — that's not background info, that's why you can recover from this load at all. Stress at 5/10 is manageable but not ideal around heavy Nordic, box jump, or top-set trap bar days. On high-stress days, keep the warm-up in and drop the finisher — the top-end work is what drives adaptation in this cycle."
      }
    ]
  }
}